osting with pasteurization. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;As for colonization temperatures of cubensis in jars, growth speeds up until an ambient of 75F, where it remains flat until 80F, and then begins to slow down.&amp;nbsp; An ambient of 83F or higher will result in a mycelium temperature approaching 90 or more, leading to slower growth and a higher incidence of failure due to bacteria and thermophilic molds.&amp;nbsp; Several years ago, I ran tightly controlled tests over a variety of 'strains', and repeated them three times, intending to average the results.&amp;nbsp; However, there was little to no variance in results over these runs.&amp;nbsp; Since that time, those same temperature ranges have been used by countless growers, and they've reported lower rates of contamination at lower temps.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>11873957</next>\n<prev>11873821</prev>\n<first>11868597</first>\n<last>12280977</last>\n<when>1264119226</when>\n<utime>01/22/10 02:13 AM</utime>\n</post>"}